Sentencas: Bilayer electrolytes for low-temperature solid oxide fuel cells (LT-SOFCs) offer the potential for higher power density by lowering the ohmic area specific resistance (ASR) and increasing the open circuit voltage (OCV) of mixed ionic/electronic conducting (MIEC) type electrolyte (e.g., GDC).
Titulo: Optimizing Bilayer Electrolyte Thickness Ratios for High-Performing Low-Temperature Solid Oxide Fuel Cells

Sentencas: However, optimizing the bilayer electrolyte thickness ratio is essential to achieve high power densities at low-temperatures (650 degrees C-500 degrees C).
Titulo: Optimizing Bilayer Electrolyte Thickness Ratios for High-Performing Low-Temperature Solid Oxide Fuel Cells

Sentencas: Herein we provide a systematic study of GDC/YCSB bilayer thickness ratios on anode-supported LT-SOFCs.
Titulo: Optimizing Bilayer Electrolyte Thickness Ratios for High-Performing Low-Temperature Solid Oxide Fuel Cells

Sentencas: In all cases the bilayer maximum power density (MPD) is higher than single-layer GDC based cells with reduced ohmic ASR values.
Titulo: Optimizing Bilayer Electrolyte Thickness Ratios for High-Performing Low-Temperature Solid Oxide Fuel Cells

Sentencas: Specifically, a high MPD of similar to 1 W cm-2 at 650 degrees C was achieved on a GDC(20 mu m)/YCSB(12
Titulo: Optimizing Bilayer Electrolyte Thickness Ratios for High-Performing Low-Temperature Solid Oxide Fuel Cells

Titulo: Optimizing Bilayer Electrolyte Thickness Ratios for High-Performing Low-Temperature Solid Oxide Fuel Cells

Sentencas: Such enhancement is due to the 9.3% improvement in OCV and 36% reduction in ohmic ASR values with the addition of the YCSB layer.
Titulo: Optimizing Bilayer Electrolyte Thickness Ratios for High-Performing Low-Temperature Solid Oxide Fuel Cells

Sentencas: The reduction in ohmic ASR of the bilayer electrolyte SOFCs is due to an increase of GDC electrical conductivity caused by the lower pO2 at the YCSB/GDC interface which must be considered in optimizing the thickness ratio of the bilayer electrolyte for achieving higher power density LT-SOFCs.
